Cell.ss:Data: This file is referred to in our Technology Supplement as "V1Tmp". If you downloaded it off of the Web site given below, and it had a

Cell.Data: different name, we suggest you rename your orignal copy "V1Tmp".
For example, you could name it "V1TmpS15HW" for "Section 1.5 Homework".

Cell.ss:Data: If you want to work on different examples, make a copy and rename a new worksheet (use Edit, Move or
Copy Sheet…) for each example, before you start on each example. (Remember to click on the Copy box so that the

Cell.Data: sheet doesn't just get moved.) To rename a sheet, double-click on its index tab and type in the new name
(for example, "Section 1.5, Exercise 3"). On the "Slope & Concavity" sheet, doing an example will add a lot of yellow cells,

Cell.ss:Data: so if you want later examples to start looking like the original, copy the sheet before doing the first example (and do it on the copy)
to keep the original sheet intact. To remove a dotted-line cell/block outline, hit "Esc".
If the size of the display on your screen does not seem ideal, change it, such as to 75% or 60% (edit the value on the toolbar); or use View, Zoom if necessary.
Cells that are colored yellow are for you to enter information; blue cells show results. Sometimes, you enter a formula in one cell, but it's likely to spill onto
later cells - we've colored them yellow too. To enter or change a formula, click on the leftmost cell where it starts. Remember to always use an

ss:Data.Font: . Excel evaluates "=-3^2-3" as 9 (not the standard -12), so "-x2-x" in a formula must be, e.g., "=-1*a13^2-a13"

Cell.ss:Data: (a leading minus sign in front of an even power should be written as "-1*").
When making entries (such as the data for the Basic Logistic Regression sheet), be sure that nothing unwanted remains

Cell.Data: from what was there before (delete the old one, or double-check your entries).
